Task 3 — Form & Visualisation Redesign
Our task was about improving the myDAISY submission form alongside making it more visually appealing and easier to understand.
Addressing the problems we found
During our research on the current website we noticed some unnecessary repetition and unconventional UX patterns. The most obvious issue was in the questions themselves — every single question started with the same long phrase, and the 2050 version of each question repeated that same opening plus added another sentence at the end. This repetition added length without adding meaning, so shortening the questions was necessary.
In both designs we kept the total number of questions exactly the same. What we addressed as the main problem was the advanced vocabulary and the length of each question. We rewrote them to be shorter and to use more common, everyday words that are easier to understand — while making sure every rewrite kept exactly the same meaning as the original.
The graph
We had a different vision for where the diagram should live. Instead of showing it only at the end after submission, we moved it to the right side of the screen so users get a live preview that updates as they fill in the form. The graph was also redesigned to show score information for each question, so users can see how each answer is contributing to their overall profile in real time.¸
A note on the graph
It is also worth clarifying that the live graph visible on the right side of the screen during the form is present for presentation and documentation purposes only — it illustrates how the final output will look and updates to give a sense of the diagram taking shape, but it is not the final deliverable. The complete, official graph is only revealed once the user has finished both the sliders and the follow-up survey.
Design 1
For our first design, and taking into account the changes to the questions, we rearranged the sliders and questions into a cleaner layout that is easier for non-researchers to follow. We also recognised that many users would be filling in the survey on their mobile phones, so we made this design extremely mobile-friendly — with large touch targets, single-column layout, and controls that work comfortably on a small screen.
Design 2
In this design we focused on a table-based solution that would be preferred by desktop users. We kept the same live graph as in Design 1, but rearranged the elements — questions, sliders, and graph — into a three-column table structure that is faster to scan and more familiar to users who are used to working in spreadsheets.
Future upgrades
We believe restructuring the order of the form would significantly increase completion rates. Rather than asking users for their project information upfront and then presenting the questions, we propose flipping the sequence: users fill in the sliders first, and once they complete them, they are shown a short survey — after which they receive their finished graph as a reward.
This works because of how the human brain responds to reward systems. When users complete the sliders they have already done the hard work, and they can sense the graph is close — it creates a feeling of being almost there. The short survey at that point feels like a small final step rather than a barrier at the start. Crucially, the graph is framed as something earned rather than something given, which makes users far more likely to push through to the end. This is the same psychological principle behind progress bars, loyalty stamps, and level systems — the closer a person feels to a reward, the more motivated they are to complete the remaining steps. Putting the survey at the end takes advantage of this natural drive rather than fighting against it.
In contrast, placing the survey at the very beginning — before users have done anything — means they are being asked to give information before they have any stake in the outcome. There is no momentum, no sense of investment, and no reward in sight. Many users will simply close the tab.
